┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│             RABBITMQ (Message Broker)                                   │
│                                                                         │
│  playbook_queue          ← work items { runId, nodeId, data }           │
│  playbook_events         ← topic exchange (all execution events)        │
│  playbook_events_broadcast ← subscribed by backend                     │
│  alarm_events            ← alarm triggers from backend                 │
│  python_exec_requests    ← RPC to code-exec-service                    │
└──────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────┘
                                   │ playbook_events_broadcast
                                   ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              BACKEND (playbookRealtime.js)                              │
│                                                                         │
│  Consumes playbook_events_broadcast queue                               │
│  ├── Deduplicates & normalizes events                                   │
│  ├── Prevents status regression (e.g., SUCCESS → RUNNING)              │
│  └── Socket.IO emit → all connected browser clients                    │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
How Modules Connect
1. Alarm Auto-Trigger Path

Alarm arrives → backend publishes to alarm_events exchange
→ alarmConsumer.js receives it
→ alarmMatchConfig.js evaluates trigger conditions vs. attached playbooks
→ runAlarmPlaybookTriggerInternal() creates PlaybookRun + first NodeExecution in DB
→ publishes { runId, nodeId } to playbook_queue
→ Worker picks it up and begins execution
2. Execution Engine Loop

Worker.js dequeues job from playbook_queue
→ loads WorkflowJSON from PlaybookVersion in DB
→ NodeRegistry.js routes to the right executor (conditional, task, soar, etc.)
→ StateResolver resolves {{Node.output}} variables from ExecutionContextCache
→ executor runs, writes outputData back to NodeExecution in DB
→ playbookQueuePublish enqueues downstream nodes (repeat)
→ playbookEventPublisher emits node.started / node.completed / node.failed
3. Real-Time UI Updates

playbookEventPublisher → playbook_events exchange
→ playbook_events_broadcast queue
→ playbookRealtime.js (backend) deduplicates
→ Socket.IO emits to frontend
→ PlaybookSocketContext.js receives event
→ useRunningPlaybooksStore updates
→ ExecutionWebSocket.js re-renders progress in canvas
4. Manual / Human-in-the-Loop Nodes

taskExecutor or decisionNode marks NodeExecution as AWAITING_INPUT
→ emits node.awaiting_input event → frontend shows ManualTaskResumeDialog
→ User submits resolveNote
→ POST /resume → resumePlaybook() controller
→ NodeExecution updated → enqueued back to playbook_queue
→ Execution continues downstream
5. Designer Save Path

Frontend canvas edit → usePlaybookDesignStore detects hasChanges
→ PATCH /api/playbooksV2/:id
→ API-Gateway proxies to Playbook-service
→ Controller updates PlaybookVersion.workflowJson + writes PlaybookAuditLog
Key Design Decisions
Pattern	Where Used	Why
Versioned workflow JSON	PlaybookVersion	In-flight runs pin to a version; edits don't break running executions
Worker process pool	workerBootstrap.js	CPU-isolated Node.js processes, configurable count
Variable interpolation	StateResolver + variables.js	Nodes pass data forward via {{NodeA.output.field}}
Tenant isolation	All DB queries + tenantContext.js	Multi-tenant SaaS — every row scoped to tenantId
Event deduplication	playbookRealtime.js	Prevents out-of-order socket events from reversing displayed status
Startup recovery	server.js	Re-enqueues PENDING/stuck-RUNNING nodes after service restart
